1. Function Signature
- Number.isInteger(value)
- Parameter: value — the value to be tested for being an integer (any JavaScript value).
- Return: boolean true if value is an integer number, otherwise false.

2. Return Semantics
- Returns true for numeric values that are mathematically integers and are representable in IEEE-754 double precision as integers.
- Returns false for NaN, Infinity, -Infinity, non-number types (strings, booleans, objects, arrays), and for non-integer finite numbers.
- For floating point numbers that are mathematically integer due to representation (e.g., 5.0000000000000001 represented as 5), the function returns true when representation equals integer.

3. Edge Cases and Precision Caveats
- JavaScript numbers are IEEE-754 doubles; very large values near Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER may lose integer fidelity, causing Number.isInteger to return true for apparent fractional inputs due to representation loss.
- Examples: Number.isInteger(5.0000000000000001) -> true because value is represented as 5. Number.isInteger(4500000000000000.1) -> true because of precision loss.
- Non-number values: Number.isInteger("10") -> false; Number.isInteger([1]) -> false.

4. Examples
- Number.isInteger(0) -> true; Number.isInteger(-100000) -> true; Number.isInteger(0.1) -> false; Number.isInteger(Math.PI) -> false; Number.isInteger(NaN) -> false; Number.isInteger(Infinity) -> false.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

Technical specifications and implementation details:
- Spec reference: ECMAScript Number.isInteger (sec-number.isinteger). The function uses type-checking and mathematical integer test: typeof value === 'number' && isFinite(value) && Math.floor(value) === value (conceptual equivalent).
- Polyfills and shims: core-js and es-shims provide polyfills for environments lacking Number.isInteger; typical polyfill pattern uses Number.isFinite and floor === value test.

